If you want to achieve a similar effect without using `<marquee>`, you can use modern HTML and CSS. The following pseudo-code outlines how you could code a tic-tac-toe board with HTML `<div>` elements and corresponding CSS styles:

```pseudo-code
// Initialize a 4x4 matrix to represent the tic-tac-toe board
board = [[empty, empty, empty, empty],
         [empty, empty, empty, empty],
         [empty, empty, empty, empty],
         [empty, empty, empty, empty]]

// Define a function to produce the tic-tac-toe HTML
FUNCTION OutputTicTacToeBoard(board):
  PRINT "<div class='tic-tac-toe-board'>"
  FOR each row in the board DO
    PRINT "<div class='tic-tac-toe-row'>"
    FOR each cell in the row DO
      PRINT "<div class='tic-tac-toe-cell'>"
      IF cell is not empty THEN
        IF cell contains 'X' THEN
          PRINT "X"
        ELSE IF cell contains 'O' THEN
          PRINT "O"
        END IF
      END IF
      PRINT "</div>"
    END FOR
    PRINT "</div>"
  END FOR
  PRINT "</div>"
END FUNCTION

CALL OutputTicTacToeBoard(board)
```

And here is what the corresponding CSS might look like:

```css
.tic-tac-toe-board {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 50px);
  grid-gap: 5px;
}

.tic-tac-toe-cell {
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  border: 1px solid #000;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  font-size: 1.5rem; /* Size of X and O */
}

.tic-tac-toe-cell:before {
  content: '';
  padding-top: 100%; /* Aspect ratio trick to keep cells square */
}

/* Optional: Add CSS for X and O if you want to style them differently */
.tic-tac-toe-cell.X {
  /* Styles for X */
}

.tic-tac-toe-cell.O {
  /* Styles for O */
}
```

This pseudo-code creates a `tic-tac-toe-board` with `tic-tac-toe-row` and `tic-tac-toe-cell` classes to layout the board and cells using CSS Grid. This will make the content more accessible and the appearance more consistent across different browsers. The CSS pseudo-element `:before` with `padding-top: 100%` is a common trick to make elements square based on their width.

The CSS I've included would create a responsive, square-cell tic-tac-toe grid without relying on outdated HTML tags. You would insert the classes 'X' or 'O' to the divs with the relevant values to apply any special styling you want for each type of mark.

Continuing from the modern HTML and CSS approach, after creating the structure with the pseudo-code and defining the styles, you would typically ensure each cell (i.e., `.tic-tac-toe-cell`) can be interacted with. For a real application, you'd add JavaScript to handle user interaction and game logic updates:

```javascript
// JavaScript (example interaction and game logic)
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const boardElement = document.querySelector('.tic-tac-toe-board');
  boardElement.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    const cell = event.target;
    if (cell.classList.contains('tic-tac-toe-cell') && cell.textContent === '') {
      // This is where you would decide whether to place an 'X' or an 'O',
      // For this example, I'll just put an 'X'
      cell.textContent = 'X';
      cell.classList.add('X');

      // Here you would also check for a win or a draw and handle that accordingly
      checkForWin();
    }
  });
});

function checkForWin() {
  // Example pseudo-code logic for checking a win or draw
