  // if there's a win, do something like display an alert or a message
  // if it's a draw (all cells filled without a win), also display a message

  // Note actual win logic not included here, as this is just meant as an outline
}
```

This basic JavaScript code listens for clicks on the board and allows placement of 'X's' into empty cells, then calls a hypothetical `checkForWin` function to see if the game is over. This function would need to be properly implemented to check the game's state for a win or a draw.

Using JavaScript, HTML, and modern CSS, you're able to create an interactive, styled tic-tac-toe game that works well across all modern browsers and devices. It's important to remember that the use of the `<marquee>` tag is considered outdated and against best practices for modern web development, as indicated in previous messages.

To complete the example, I would like to provide a more concrete approach for the JavaScript part that provides a very simple win check algorithm for the 4x4 tic-tac-toe board. The use of classes 'X' and 'O' is included in the HTML representation to simplify the win check logic within the JavaScript code.

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const boardElement = document.querySelector('.tic-tac-toe-board');

  let currentPlayer = 'X'; // Track the current player, X starts the game

  boardElement.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    const cell = event.target;
    if (cell.classList.contains('tic-tac-toe-cell') && cell.textContent === '') {
      // Place the current player's symbol in the cell
      cell.textContent = currentPlayer;
      cell.classList.add(currentPlayer);

      // Check for a win or a draw
      if (checkForWin(currentPlayer)) {
        alert(currentPlayer + ' wins!');
        // You may want to restart the game or disable further clicks here
      } else if (isBoardFull()) {
        alert('Draw!');
        // You may also want to restart the game or disable further clicks here
      }

      // Switch the current player for the next turn
      currentPlayer = currentPlayer === 'X' ? 'O' : 'X';
    }
  });
});


// Checks if a player has won
function checkForWin(playerClass) {
  // You will need to implement all winning condition checks here.
  // For simplicity, we'll check only rows and you would need to expand it to check columns, diagonals, etc.
  const WINNING_COMBO_LENGTH = 4;
  const rows = document.querySelectorAll('.tic-tac-toe-row');

  for (let row of rows) {
    let score = 0;
    let cells = row.querySelectorAll('.tic-tac-toe-cell');

    for (let cell of cells) {
      if (cell.classList.contains(playerClass)) {
        score++;
      }
    }

    if (score === WINNING_COMBO_LENGTH) {
      return true; // Found a winning row
    }
  }

  // Here you should continue the logic to check for columns, diagonals, etc.

  return false; // No win found
}

// Checks if all cells on the board are filled
function isBoardFull() {
  const cells = document.querySelectorAll('.tic-tac-toe-cell');
  return [...cells].every(cell => cell.textContent.trim() !== '');
}
```

This code now includes a basic check to determine if a win occurs by going through each row and seeing if all cells in that row contain the same symbol, 'X' or 'O'. This approach needs to be extended to include column checks and diagonal checks for a complete win verification algorithm.

After each turn, we switch the `currentPlayer` to the other player. If there's a win or a draw, an alert message is shown, and the game should be appropriately reset or further interaction should be disabled according to the desired game flow.

This is just a starting point and not a complete game implementation, you would still need to build proper game reset logic and likely enhance the user experience beyond simple `alert` messages. Additionally, you should implement checks for wins on columns, diagonals, and possibly detect draws in a more sophisticated way.

This code snippet combined with the previous HTML and CSS should give you a good foundation for creating a fully interactive 4x4 tic-tac-toe board.

